{
  "Idea": "We propose DynaMixer-3D: Dynamic Channel-wise Mixture of 1D/2D/3D Kernels via Content-Adaptive Hypernetworks—a novel framework that redefines 3D convolutional computation by enabling each output channel to synthesize its own optimal kernel shape and weights on-the-fly, based on the input feature's spatiotemporal structure. Unlike prior methods such as CAKES or the proposed AdaKernel-3D, which rely on discrete kernel selection or static architecture search, DynaMixer-3D treats kernel dimensionality as a continuous, learnable property. At the core of our method is a lightweight hypernetwork module attached to each 3D convolution layer, which takes channel-local feature patches and generates a mixture of 1D (temporal or axial-spatial), 2D (spatial-plane), and 3D (volumetric) kernels per channel. The hypernetwork outputs both the weights of these sub-kernels and soft routing coefficients that determine their blending proportions. Crucially, the kernel generation is conditioned on input content—allowing dynamic shifts in representational strategy (e.g., from motion tracking to texture analysis) without architectural changes. To ensure efficiency, we factorize the hypernetwork using low-rank parameterizations (e.g., rank-2 modulation) and constrain the total number of floating-point operations via a sparsity-inducing loss that encourages dominant contributions from at most two kernel types per channel, promoting complementary specialization. During training, we use Gumbel-Softmax relaxation to enable end-to-end optimization of the routing policy, while at inference, we apply top-k sparsification (k=1 or 2) for speed. This results in a highly adaptive 3D network where channels autonomously specialize: some evolve into efficient temporal filters, others into planar detectors, and only when necessary do they engage full 3D computation. The emergent heterogeneity improves both accuracy and efficiency by aligning computational effort with semantic demand. We validate DynaMixer-3D on video action recognition (Kinetics-400, Something-Something V2) and 3D medical segmentation (BraTS, Medical Decathlon), demonstrating >45% FLOPs reduction with <0.5% accuracy drop compared to dense 3D CNNs, and outperforming CAKES and AdaKernel-3D in both parameter efficiency and cross-dataset generalization. Our framework opens a new paradigm: instead of pruning or selecting from predefined operators, we *generate* them adaptively—ushering in a new class of self-configuring 3D networks.",
